'''Adler & Sullivan''' was an [[architectural firm]] founded by [[Dankmar Adler]] and [[Louis Sullivan]]. It is known for designing the [[Auditorium Building]] in Chicago<ref>{{cite book|last=Korom|first=Joseph J.|title=The American Skyscraper, 1850-1940: A Celebration of Height|year=2008|publisher=Branden Books|isbn=0-8283-2188-4|pages=495}}</ref> and the [[Wainwright Building]] in St Louis.<ref>{{cite book|last=Korom|first=Joseph J.|title=The American Skyscraper, 1850-1940: A Celebration of Height|year=2008|publisher=Branden Books|isbn=0-8283-2188-4|pages=507}}</ref> In 1883 Louis Sullivan was added to Adler's architectural firm, creating the Adler & Sullivan partnership.<ref>{{cite book|last=Morrison|first=Hugh|title=Louis Sullivan, prophet of modern architecture|year=2001|publisher=Norton, W. W. & Company, Inc|isbn=0-393-32161-4|pages=262|author2=Timothy J. Samuelson}}</ref>
